# TypeScript & Vue SFC Conventions

## TypeScript

- Use `type` over `interface` for all type definitions.
- Avoid enums; use `const` objects with `as const` instead.
- Use inline type imports: `import { type Foo } from './foo'`.
- Prefer `type` assertions only when narrowing is not possible.

```ts
// ❌ BAD
interface User { id: string }
enum Status { Active = 'active' }

// ✅ GOOD
type User = { id: string }
const STATUS = { Active: 'active', Paused: 'paused' } as const
type Status = typeof STATUS[keyof typeof STATUS]
```

## Naming Conventions

- Directories: `lowercase-with-dashes` (e.g., `auth-wizard/`)
- Components: `PascalCase.vue` (e.g., `AuthWizard.vue`)
- Composables: `camelCase.ts` prefixed with `use` (e.g., `useAuthState.ts`)
- Event handlers: prefix with `handle` (e.g., `handleClick`, `handleKeyDown`)
- Boolean variables: auxiliary verb prefix (e.g., `isLoading`, `hasError`, `canSubmit`)

## Vue SFC Structure

Block order is always: `<script>` → `<template>` → `<style>`. Add a blank line between blocks.

```vue
<script setup lang="ts">
// logic here
</script>

<template>
  <!-- markup here -->
</template>

<style scoped>
/* only when Tailwind is not sufficient */
</style>
```

- Always use `<script setup lang="ts">`.
- Use arrow functions for methods and computed properties.
- Prefer early returns to reduce nesting.
- Delete unused variables, functions, and imports in every file you touch.
- Nuxt auto-imports Vue primitives (`ref`, `computed`, `watch`) — do not import them manually.
